#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:575
msgid ""
"\\ **Submatrix**: Assignment to a submatrix can be done with lists of "
"indices using the ``ix_`` command. E.g., for 2D array ``a``, one might do: "
"``ind=[1, 3]; a[np.ix_(ind, ind)] += 100``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:579
msgid ""
"\\ **HELP**: There is no direct equivalent of MATLAB's ``which`` command, "
"but the commands :func:`help` will usually list the filename where the "
"function is located. Python also has an ``inspect`` module (do ``import "
"inspect``) which provides a ``getfile`` that often works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:584
msgid ""
"\\ **INDEXING**: MATLAB uses one based indexing, so the initial element of a "
"sequence has index 1. Python uses zero based indexing, so the initial "
"element of a sequence has index 0. Confusion and flamewars arise because "
"each has advantages and disadvantages. One based indexing is consistent with "
"common human language usage, where the \"first\" element of a sequence has "
"index 1. Zero based indexing `simplifies indexing <https://groups.google.com/"
"group/comp.lang.python/msg/1bf4d925dfbf368?q=g:thl3498076713d&hl=en>`__. See "
"also `a text by prof.dr. Edsger W. Dijkstra <https://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/"
"EWD/transcriptions/EWD08xx/EWD831.html>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:594
msgid ""
"\\ **RANGES**: In MATLAB, ``0:5`` can be used as both a range literal and a "
"'slice' index (inside parentheses); however, in Python, constructs like "
"``0:5`` can *only* be used as a slice index (inside square brackets). Thus "
"the somewhat quirky ``r_`` object was created to allow NumPy to have a "
"similarly terse range construction mechanism. Note that ``r_`` is not called "
"like a function or a constructor, but rather *indexed* using square "
"brackets, which allows the use of Python's slice syntax in the arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:603
msgid ""
"\\ **LOGICOPS**: ``&`` or ``|`` in NumPy is bitwise AND/OR, while in MATLAB "
"& and ``|`` are logical AND/OR. The two can appear to work the same, but "
"there are important differences. If you would have used MATLAB's ``&`` or ``|"
"`` operators, you should use the NumPy ufuncs ``logical_and``/"
"``logical_or``. The notable differences between MATLAB's and NumPy's ``&`` "
"and ``|`` operators are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:610
msgid ""
"Non-logical {0,1} inputs: NumPy's output is the bitwise AND of the inputs. "
"MATLAB treats any non-zero value as 1 and returns the logical AND. For "
"example ``(3 & 4)`` in NumPy is ``0``, while in MATLAB both ``3`` and ``4`` "
"are considered logical true and ``(3 & 4)`` returns ``1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:616
msgid ""
"Precedence: NumPy's & operator is higher precedence than logical operators "
"like ``<`` and ``>``; MATLAB's is the reverse."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:619
msgid ""
"If you know you have boolean arguments, you can get away with using NumPy's "
"bitwise operators, but be careful with parentheses, like this: ``z = (x > 1) "
"& (x < 2)``. The absence of NumPy operator forms of ``logical_and`` and "
"``logical_or`` is an unfortunate consequence of Python's design."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:624
msgid ""
"**RESHAPE and LINEAR INDEXING**: MATLAB always allows multi-dimensional "
"arrays to be accessed using scalar or linear indices, NumPy does not. Linear "
"indices are common in MATLAB programs, e.g. ``find()`` on a matrix returns "
"them, whereas NumPy's find behaves differently. When converting MATLAB code "
"it might be necessary to first reshape a matrix to a linear sequence, "
"perform some indexing operations and then reshape back. As reshape (usually) "
"produces views onto the same storage, it should be possible to do this "
"fairly efficiently. Note that the scan order used by reshape in NumPy "
"defaults to the 'C' order, whereas MATLAB uses the Fortran order. If you are "
"simply converting to a linear sequence and back this doesn't matter. But if "
"you are converting reshapes from MATLAB code which relies on the scan order, "
"then this MATLAB code: ``z = reshape(x,3,4);`` should become ``z = x."
"reshape(3,4,order='F').copy()`` in NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:640
msgid "'array' or 'matrix'? Which should I use?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:642
msgid ""
"Historically, NumPy has provided a special matrix type, `np.matrix`, which "
"is a subclass of ndarray which makes binary operations linear algebra "
"operations. You may see it used in some existing code instead of `np.array`. "
"So, which one to use?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:648
msgid "Short answer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:650
msgid "**Use arrays**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:652
msgid "They support multidimensional array algebra that is supported in MATLAB"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:653
msgid ""
"They are the standard vector/matrix/tensor type of NumPy. Many NumPy "
"functions return arrays, not matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:655
msgid ""
"There is a clear distinction between element-wise operations and linear "
"algebra operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:657
msgid "You can have standard vectors or row/column vectors if you like."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:659
msgid ""
"Until Python 3.5 the only disadvantage of using the array type was that you "
"had to use ``dot`` instead of ``*`` to multiply (reduce) two tensors (scalar "
"product, matrix vector multiplication etc.). Since Python 3.5 you can use "
"the matrix multiplication ``@`` operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:664
msgid "Given the above, we intend to deprecate ``matrix`` eventually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:667
msgid "Long answer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:669
msgid ""
"NumPy contains both an ``array`` class and a ``matrix`` class. The ``array`` "
"class is intended to be a general-purpose n-dimensional array for many kinds "
"of numerical computing, while ``matrix`` is intended to facilitate linear "
"algebra computations specifically. In practice there are only a handful of "
"key differences between the two."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:675
msgid "Operators ``*`` and ``@``, functions ``dot()``, and ``multiply()``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:677
msgid ""
"For ``array``, ``*`` **means element-wise multiplication**, while ``@`` "
"**means matrix multiplication**; they have associated functions "
"``multiply()`` and ``dot()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:680
msgid ""
"For ``matrix``, ``*`` **means matrix multiplication**, and for element-wise "
"multiplication one has to use the ``multiply()`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:683
msgid "Handling of vectors (one-dimensional arrays)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:685
msgid ""
"For ``array``, the **vector shapes 1xN, Nx1, and N are all different "
"things**. Operations like ``A[:,1]`` return a one-dimensional array of shape "
"N, not a two-dimensional array of shape Nx1. Transpose on a one-dimensional "
"``array`` does nothing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:689
msgid ""
"For ``matrix``, **one-dimensional arrays are always upconverted to 1xN or "
"Nx1 matrices** (row or column vectors). ``A[:,1]`` returns a two-dimensional "
"matrix of shape Nx1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:693
msgid "Handling of higher-dimensional arrays (ndim > 2)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:695
msgid "``array`` objects **can have number of dimensions > 2**;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:696
msgid "``matrix`` objects **always have exactly two dimensions**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:698
msgid "Convenience attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:700
msgid ""
"``array`` **has a .T attribute**, which returns the transpose of the data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:702
msgid ""
"``matrix`` **also has .H, .I, and .A attributes**, which return the "
"conjugate transpose, inverse, and ``asarray()`` of the matrix, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:706
msgid "Convenience constructor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:708
msgid ""
"The ``array`` constructor **takes (nested) Python sequences as "
"initializers**. As in, ``array([[1,2,3],[4,5,6]])``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:710
msgid ""
"The ``matrix`` constructor additionally **takes a convenient string "
"initializer**. As in ``matrix(\"[1 2 3; 4 5 6]\")``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:713
msgid "There are pros and cons to using both:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:715
msgid "``array``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:717
msgid "``:)`` Element-wise multiplication is easy: ``A*B``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:718
msgid ""
"``:(`` You have to remember that matrix multiplication has its own operator, "
"``@``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:720
msgid ""
"``:)`` You can treat one-dimensional arrays as *either* row or column "
"vectors. ``A @ v`` treats ``v`` as a column vector, while ``v @ A`` treats "
"``v`` as a row vector. This can save you having to type a lot of transposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:724
msgid ""
"``:)`` ``array`` is the \"default\" NumPy type, so it gets the most testing, "
"and is the type most likely to be returned by 3rd party code that uses NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:727
msgid "``:)`` Is quite at home handling data of any number of dimensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:728
msgid ""
"``:)`` Closer in semantics to tensor algebra, if you are familiar with that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:730
msgid ""
"``:)`` *All* operations (``*``, ``/``, ``+``, ``-`` etc.) are element-wise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:732
msgid ""
"``:(`` Sparse matrices from ``scipy.sparse`` do not interact as well with "
"arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:735
msgid "``matrix``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:737
msgid "``:\\\\`` Behavior is more like that of MATLAB matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:738
msgid ""
"``<:(`` Maximum of two-dimensional. To hold three-dimensional data you need "
"``array`` or perhaps a Python list of ``matrix``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:740
msgid ""
"``<:(`` Minimum of two-dimensional. You cannot have vectors. They must be "
"cast as single-column or single-row matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:742
msgid ""
"``<:(`` Since ``array`` is the default in NumPy, some functions may return "
"an ``array`` even if you give them a ``matrix`` as an argument. This "
"shouldn't happen with NumPy functions (if it does it's a bug), but 3rd party "
"code based on NumPy may not honor type preservation like NumPy does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:747
msgid ""
"``:)`` ``A*B`` is matrix multiplication, so it looks just like you write it "
"in linear algebra (For Python >= 3.5 plain arrays have the same convenience "
"with the ``@`` operator)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:750
msgid ""
"``<:(`` Element-wise multiplication requires calling a function, "
"``multiply(A,B)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:752
msgid ""
"``<:(`` The use of operator overloading is a bit illogical: ``*`` does not "
"work element-wise but ``/`` does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:754
msgid "Interaction with ``scipy.sparse`` is a bit cleaner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:756
msgid ""
"The ``array`` is thus much more advisable to use.  Indeed, we intend to "
"deprecate ``matrix`` eventually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:760
msgid "Customizing your environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:762
msgid ""
"In MATLAB the main tool available to you for customizing the environment is "
"to modify the search path with the locations of your favorite functions. You "
"can put such customizations into a startup script that MATLAB will run on "
"startup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:767
msgid "NumPy, or rather Python, has similar facilities."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:769
msgid ""
"To modify your Python search path to include the locations of your own "
"modules, define the ``PYTHONPATH`` environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:772
msgid ""
"To have a particular script file executed when the interactive Python "
"interpreter is started, define the ``PYTHONSTARTUP`` environment variable to "
"contain the name of your startup script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:776
msgid ""
"Unlike MATLAB, where anything on your path can be called immediately, with "
"Python you need to first do an 'import' statement to make functions in a "
"particular file accessible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:780
msgid ""
"For example you might make a startup script that looks like this (Note: this "
"is just an example, not a statement of \"best practices\"):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:785
msgid ""
"# Make all numpy available via shorter 'np' prefix\n"
"import numpy as np\n"
"#\n"
"# Make the SciPy linear algebra functions available as linalg.func()\n"
"# e.g. linalg.lu, linalg.eig (for general l*B@u==A@u solution)\n"
"from scipy import linalg\n"
"#\n"
"# Define a Hermitian function\n"
"def hermitian(A, **kwargs):\n"
"    return np.conj(A,**kwargs).T\n"
"# Make a shortcut for hermitian:\n"
"#    hermitian(A) --> H(A)\n"
"H = hermitian"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:799
msgid "To use the deprecated `matrix` and other `matlib` functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/numpy-for-matlab-users.rst:803
msgid ""
"# Make all matlib functions accessible at the top level via M.func()\n"
"import numpy.matlib as M\n"
"# Make some matlib functions accessible directly at the top level via, e.g. "
"rand(3,3)\n"
"from numpy.matlib import matrix,rand,zeros,ones,empty,eye"
msgstr ""

